bug.short_desc: Part Collapsing results in Circular Dependencies

long_desc.thetext:
Part collapsing can result in circular dependencies, where a package A receives a smaller package with dependency to package B, and package B receives a smaller package with dependency to A. The generator issues a corresponding warning like:
Warning: Circular dependencies between packages: #7 - #15
In this particular case, this doesn't seem to result in a problem, as #7 is merged into #15 and therefore both dependencies are resolved. After part collapsing, the generated app seems to work fine (at least the OP didn't speak to the contrary).
The question is whether this situation can be avoided altogether. (See attached generator output).
Created attachment 874 generator -v output, showing part collapsing

Here is another scenario:
Part boot Part A includes Part A1 includes Part A2 and A3 Part B
Parts A1-3 are in a different subproject. The include tree looks like this:
boot I---A I I---A1 I I---A2 I I---A3 I---B
We get:
Warning: Circular dependencies between packages: #15 - #63

- Package #63 depends on these packages: []
>>> Part summary : 6 parts - Part #B packages(7): #63, #59, #27, #15, #11, #49, #1 - Part #A1 packages(7): #63, #59, #58, #49, #52, #48, #32 - Part #boot packages(4): #63, #15, #52, #4 - Part #A2 packages(9): #63, #59, #27, #15, #58, #11, #26, #10, #8 - Part #A packages(9): #63, #59, #27, #58, #49, #52, #26, #48, #16 - Part #A3 packages(9): #63, #59, #27, #15, #58, #11, #26, #10, #2
Where is the circular dependency? As far as we can see it is straight include.

Moved the 'Circular dependencies' warning to debug level, as several people found it irritating.
With r25769

Additional consistency checks have been implemented, to make part configuration and generation more robust:
- part config's "include" lists must be overlap-free - one part must not contain load dependencies of another part - the set of the classes of all parts must match the global class list of the app
